The changes were by no means universal, but the way that police agencies and execs talked about certain issues changed. It wasn't just #BLM, it was also the opiate epidemic, expansion of social media, etc. But the short answer is yes - changes have continued.

President Obama's Task Force on 21st Century Policing was created as a direct response to events in the summer of 2014. #BLM had been around for about two years, I think, since the 2012 killing of Trayvon Martin, but really jumped to national prominence that summer.

Policing as an industry, and some agencies specifically, have continued to evolve after #BLM. That movement contributed to an increased public scrutiny of policing over an extended period of time, which can exert the type of political influence that forces change.
